## Conventions (carried over from prior libs — port verbatim)

- Conventional Commits + `release-please` + PR title lint
- Scripts-first CI surface — every non-trivial step in `scripts/ci/*.sh` with `set -euo pipefail`
- Post-publish verification trio: `mix verify.workspace_clean`, `mix verify.release_publish`, `mix verify.release_parity`
- Daily drift cron with single rolling GitHub issue (`JasonEtco/create-an-issue@v2`, `update_existing: true`)
- 3-folder guides split: `introduction/` / `flows/` / `recipes/`
- `api_stability.md` enumerates locked public surface
- `CONVENTIONS.md` codifies discipline rules (paired with custom Credo checks)
- Fake adapter as merge-gate target (real-Postgres integration tests run nightly)
- Golden-diff installer test under `test/fixtures/install_golden/{tree,STDOUT.txt}` with timestamp normalization
- Hex `package.files` whitelist (never auto-include whole repo; never include `test/example/`, `*_ops/`, `.planning/`, `prompts/`)
- Per-phase `mix verify.phaseNN` tasks (never a kitchen-sink verifier)

## What NOT to do

- Don't re-derive research — `prompts/` anchor docs are already research-grade; use them directly.
- Don't compete with LaunchDarkly as a hosted platform. Rulestead is self-hostable OSS.
- Don't build a stats engine for experiments. Expose impression/tracking hooks; analytics lives in the user's warehouse.
- Don't make DB reads the default runtime evaluation path.
- Don't hide precedence in clever magic.
- Don't make flag creation work without owner + expected_expiration.
- Don't use percentage-of-time as a first-class rollout type (research brief §6.1 footgun).
- Don't bundle an auth stack.
- Don't put `:email`, `:ip`, `:user_agent`, `:phone`, `:name`, or similar raw traits into telemetry meta or Logger metadata.
